---
title: "How to Design Team Habits Into Your Operations System, Not Just Your Meetings"
date: "2023-06-07"
summary: "Build team habits into your operations system. Habits enforced by systems last. Habits enforced by meetings fade."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Habit Systems"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your team has a weekly review meeting. The meeting is productive when everyone attends. The habit dies when someone is out. The meeting is fragile. The habit should not be.

A team habit is a behavior the team performs consistently. Not because someone reminded them. Because the system requires it.

Here is how to design habits into the system.

Define the behavior. What should the team do. Every Friday, review the metrics. Every Monday, check the backlog. Every day, update the ticket status. The behavior is specific.

Build the trigger into the system. The system prompts the behavior. Not a calendar invite. The system. On Friday at 2 PM, the dashboard shows the weekly review view. On Monday morning, the backlog is the first thing the team sees. The system triggers the behavior.

Make the behavior visible. When the behavior is performed, the team can see it. The review is logged. The backlog update is timestamped. The visibility reinforces the habit.

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we designed system-enforced habits. The team had been relying on meetings to enforce habits. When someone was out, the habit was missed. We built the habits into the system. The habits became consistent. The meetings became optional.

The teams that rely on meetings are the ones with fragile habits. The teams that build habits into the system are the ones with durable habits.

Define the behavior. Build the trigger. Make it visible. The habit lasts.
